Male terminalia (
Figs. 87–90
): Sternite 5 with several long bristles posterolaterally, medially with pale, microtrichose, desclerotized area in front of field of enlarged microtrichia; hind margin with 6–10 scales of subequal length. Epandrium with numerous long bristles ventrally. Anterior section of surstylus with apex of anterior process moderately pointed (intermediate between 

L. papallacta

sp.n.
and 

L. mendozana

), ventral lobe little produced, with several relatively long bristles. Posterior section of surstylus with a small, inconspicuous tooth-like process anteriorly near base (lateral view), apex with the usual two strong bristles (lateral one shorter and with blunt tip), posterior surface with numerous long pale hairs crowded in lateral half (hairs less numerous than in 

L. mendozana

). Cercus with transparent, lamellate medial process. Postgonite with narrow posterobasal notch (
Fig. 140
).

Female terminalia (
Figs. 91–93
): Tergite 7 long and strongly convex, anteriorly with a pair of strong, cruciate bristles; medial stripe in posterior 4/5–1/2 and hind margin shining, lacking tomentosity. Sternite 7 with thickened and narrowly shining hind margin (often difficult to appreciate in slightly teneral specimens). Fused tergite 10 + cerci short, with short hairs. Spermathecae elongate, with weakly striate surface.
